We recommended that Management:
Ensure that guidelines are set in writing in selecting intended recipients of the EDF projects;
Elaborate technical specifications of the project to address the technical requirements, particularly  on the  supply of water system;
Consider other means of improving water supply to the LGU Barangays such as the supply of piped water to ensure clean water; and
Ensure proper planning, implementation, and evaluation of the projects funded by 20% LDF.

We recommended that Management require the: 

 Municipal Treasurer being the Chairperson of the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all PPE using the prescribed format, maintain individual property card for all PPE owned by the LGU and ensure completeness of the ARE and the inventory report;

Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete PPELC to ensure proper monitoring, make the necessary adjusting entries on the properties not computed with depreciation; and exert extra efforts to locate the details and breakdown of the inherited/beginning balances and the properties with no complete descriptions; 

Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile noted discrepancies; and

Undertake the necessary action/s for the disposal of the unserviceable properties to avoid further deterioration and consequent depreciation in its value.

Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; Inventory Committee to   conduct an inventory of the local roads and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;

Municipal Treasurer to: (a) prepare a Report on Local Road Network; (b)maintain local road inventory and road map; and (c) maintain property cards for all roads and its components; and

Municipal Accountant to: (a) maintain subsidiary ledger cards for roads and road components for every road network; and (b) prepare lapsing schedule showing the computation of the depreciation of each component of the Road Network System account.

Fast track the reconciliation of Due to GSIS, Due to Pag-ibig and Due to Philhealth accounts;

and

Settle immediately the unremitted GSIS, Pag-ibig, Philhealth premiums (personal and government share) and loan amortizations deducted from the salaries of the employees to avoid any sanctions that may be imposed due to late or non-remittance.

Insure all of their properties with the GSIS GIF to avoid exposure from unnecessary risk;

Prepare and submit the Property Inventory Form (PIF) listing of all insurable assets showing their latest appraised values/valuation, appraisal date, location, and other information;

Incorporate in their annual budget the amount of insurance premiums to be paid;

Renew the expired insurance policy of all motor vehicles; and


Secure the copy of Deed of Donation and other documents needed in order to register the fire truck with the LTO and be the subject of insurance policy with the GSIS GIF.

We recommended that Management:

Submit the supplemental budget for the amount of ₱ 3.515 million;

Stop, or minimize the granting of cash advances for COVID-19 related expense;

Strictly abide by the rules, laws and regulations on government procurement for emergency cases as discussed in GPBB Circular No. 01-2020;

Ensure that all COVID-19 funds are utilized only for COVID-19 related expenses; and 

Require the Municipal Accountant to verify the completeness of attached supporting documents before payment is made.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Engineer to closely monitor the implementation and completion of the projects;

Assign/hire new Engineers who could assist the Municipal Engineer in his duties; 

Immediately implement the projects for CY 2020; and

Submit the Consolidated Report of Government PPAs quarterly or as may be requested from time to time for audit purposes.

We recommended that Management:

require the supplier to change the delivered 2 units LED monitor (43”and 32”) with 50” monitor being the requirement of the LGU as stated in the Purchase Order, else the amount of ₱87,284 pertaining to the cost of delivered monitors shall be disallowed in audit;

require the concerned LGU official/employee to refund the amount of ₱950.00 pertaining to undelivered items pending issuance of Notice of Disallowance; 

instruct the BAC to be cautious in the         review/verification of the submitted documents by prospective suppliers/bidders; and 


ensure that in the preparation of Purchase Request/s, deliverables including its specifications are properly indicated.

We recommended to the management to require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that:

GJs and JEVs prepared are signed by the preparer/bookkeeper and duly approved;

all entries reflected in the GJs are: 1) supported with supporting documents and JEVs; 2) account titles of the affected account/s are indicated aside from the account code in the GJ; and 3) have complete description/explanation of the journal entries made.

We recommended that Management submit the following documents:

signed MOA between the LGU and the DOLE; 

the individual profiles, plans and business proposals that served as basis of the LGU in the selection process of the beneficiaries; and

the lacking acknowledgement receipts on the distributed nego-karts to the beneficiaries. 

We further recommended that Management: 

execute a MOA with the existing identified beneficiaries of the project containing the terms and conditions as well as their individual responsibilities on the use of the nego-karts;

justification on why 10 recipients of nego-karts whose names were not included in the summary of beneficiary template were able to receive the nego-karts; 

require the Project Coordinator to regularly monitor the status of the awarded nego-karts taking into consideration the economic benefit, if any brought to the lives of the awardee beneficiaries followed with monitoring reports that may be used in future livelihood projects; 

direct the concerned liable LGU employee/s to refund the amount of ₱51,049.60, representing the cost of four undelivered nego-karts pending issuance of Notice of Disallowance; and 

ensure that the terms and conditions of the MOA/Approved Project Proposal on fund transfers from other government agencies are faithfully followed.

We recommended that Management require the:

passage of a valid ordinance covering wharf and the Camaligan River Cruise Rental; 

Tourism Officer, Internal Auditor, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to: (a) convene and design a system of procedures with built-in internal controls such that identified weaknesses under the second sub-topic be addressed; (b) revisit and re-evaluate propriety of costing  and projections in coming up with revised rates/ fees; (c) investigate and determine the reasons for the inconsistent imposition of the Rental Fee and EUF; and (d) look into collecting the under remittance worth ₱8,550 from FBC;

Stoppage of the practice of immediately deducting and remitting food and beverage cost to FBC Concessionaire out of daily collections such that payments to FBC must follow usual disbursement procedures; and

Designate only properly bonded official/employee who shall receive money and issue receipts from patrons of Camaligan River Cruise.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:      

transfer the unutilized fund for CY2018 to Trust Liability-DRRM account in the Trust Fund books; 

observe proper recording of transactions and submit the detailed distribution list of the distributed 100 sacks of rice to forestall the issuance of Notice of Suspension.

We recommended that Management:

 require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the difference in the reports and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the balance of RPT/SET Receivables and deferred RPT/SET;

request from LGU Camarines Sur the details of collection of the RPT and SET amounting to P108,744.00 and  P9,020.88, respectively and prepare the necessary adjusting entries and update the Registry of Real Property Tax book.

We recommended that Management:
direct the Property Custodian to maintain individual property card for all PPE owned by the LGU and ensure completeness of the PAR;
require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete and timely PPELC to ensure proper monitoring of PPE;
instruct the Accounting and Property Office to validate and identify the noted differences between the accounting records and RPCPPE that may require adjustment/s;
undertake the necessary action/s for the disposal of the unserviceable properties to avoid further deterioration and consequent depreciation of the assets;
exert efforts to identify breakdown of inherited balance and take necessary actions for reconciliation; and
reconcile and identify reasons for discrepancy for accumulated balances and note the items that need adjustments.

We recommended that Management require the:
Municipal Accountant to identify the details of the reconciling items and prepare the necessary accounting/adjusting entries and establish the liability of the LGU officials concerned;
Municipal Treasurer to: (1) maintain a record of all accountable forms purchased and used; and (2) stop maintaining pre signed checks for all accounts;
Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to: (1) conduct reconciliation of cashbook and accounting records balances on a regular basis; (2) exert efforts in order to locate the details of the time deposit account; and (3) identify the employee or official accountable for the account and impose sanctions if warranted.

We recommended that Management:
exert efforts to locate the details of accountable officers with no available data and issue demand letters to notify them to settle the unliquidated cash advances;
send final demand letters to persons previously connected with the Municipality who still have unliquidated cash advances, otherwise, officials responsible for clearing said individuals from money accountability be held liable for the unsettled cash advances;
cause immediate liquidation or settlement from accountable officers from other government agencies; and
require the Municipal Treasurer to settle immediately his outstanding cash advances and stop the practice of granting cash advance/s to the Municipal Treasurer for the different activities of the LGU unless previous cash advances had been settled/liquidated

We recommended that Management require the:
Municipal Accountant to identify the details of the reconciling items and prepare the necessary accounting/adjusting entries and revert back to the appropriate funds the stale checks and establish the liability of the LGU officials concerned;

Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to conduct reconciliation of cashbook and accounting records balances on a regular basis.

